                    <seg corresp="#KR2o0001_tls_039-h.1" xml:lang="en" resp="#paulfahr" modified="2024-03-07T19:46:12.347+09:00">Doubting Antiquity?</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2o0001_tls_039-1a.11" xml:lang="en" resp="#Lea.Wallraff" modified="2024-04-24T16:45:40.29+09:00"/>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2o0001_tls_039-1a.7" xml:lang="en" resp="#paulfahr" modified="2024-03-07T19:47:55.864+09:00">This and the following line refers to the respective chapters in Shangshu.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2o0001_tls_039-1a.12" xml:lang="en" resp="#paulfahr" modified="2024-03-07T19:50:15.399+09:00">The idea seems to be that these later orators without exception refer to the aforementioned older speeches as documented in Shangshu and elsewhere.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2o0001_tls_039-1a.15" xml:lang="en" resp="#Lea.Wallraff" modified="2024-04-24T18:12:45.229+09:00"/>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2o0001_tls_039-7a.14" xml:lang="en" resp="#Lea.Wallraff" modified="2024-04-25T19:08:23.594+09:00">note by Pu Qilong: 禮 here means the Chunqiu</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2o0001_tls_039-20a.5" xml:lang="en" resp="#Lea.Wallraff" modified="2024-04-28T19:46:02.69+09:00">春秋左傳  /  昭公</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2o0001_tls_039-20a.13" xml:lang="en" resp="#Lea.Wallraff" modified="2024-04-28T19:58:05.382+09:00">今文尚書  /  《君奭》</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2o0001_tls_039-13a.2" xml:lang="en" resp="#Lea.Wallraff" modified="2024-05-01T04:57:19.412+09:00">尚書  /  《舜典》</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2o0001_tls_039-19a.30" xml:lang="en" resp="#Lea.Wallraff" modified="2024-05-02T23:02:59.182+09:00">forthis allusion, see Chunqiu Zuozhuan, Zhao gong, 22.3: In the referencedpassage, Bin Qi 賓起 (d. 520) sees a rooster plucking out its tail feathers and hears that itdoes this in order to avoid being sacrificed. this example is then compared toa certain dispute about succession, in which the aspirant not favoured by birthright is likened to a rooster that flourishes its tail and exposes itself todanger. Taibo does not act this way but behaves like the rooster plucking itstail, since he finally agrees to go along with the change in succession,fearing the consequences that would otherwise impend. Liu Zhiji’s point seemsto be that he did not renounce the throne out of “moral authority” but merelybecause of selfish considerations.</seg>
